{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}} {{Use New Zealand English|date=August 2015}} __NOTOC__ {{Infobox political party | name = Ban 1080 Party | logo = Ban 1080 Party logo.svg | logo_size = 200px | colorcode = <!-- HTML color code (e.g. "red", "#FF0000" or Party metadata color template) otherwise "transparent" --> | founder = Bill Wallace | leader = Bill Wallace and Mike Downard | president = | chairman = | general_secretary = | first_secretary = | secretary_general = | presidium = | secretary = | spokesperson = | foundation = <!-- {{start date|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | ideology = Opposes the use of [[Sodium fluoroacetate|1080 poison]] | dissolution = {{End date and age|2018}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elections.org.nz/news-media/amendments-register-political-parties-28-february-2018 |title=Amendments to the Register of Political Parties - 28 February 2018 |publisher=Electoral Commission |date=28 February 2018 |accessdate=1 March 2018}}</ref> | headquarters = | international = | website = {{url|http://ban1080.co.nz/}} | country = New Zealand |colours = |seats1_title = MPs in the [[New Zealand House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] |seats1 = {{Composition bar|0|120|hex=}} }}
The '''Ban 1080 Party''' is an unregistered [[political party]] in [[New Zealand]]. The party was founded in 2014 by Bill Wallace. It opposes the use of [[Sodium fluoroacetate|1080 poison (sodium fluoroacetate)]], which is widely [[1080 usage in New Zealand|used in New Zealand]] for controlling mammalian pests such as [[Common brushtail possum in New Zealand#Control|possums]] and rats.<ref name=stuff1>{{cite web |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/10172333/Ban-1080-party-in-push-for-election |title=Ban 1080 party in push for election |publisher=Stuff |date=2014-06-18 |accessdate=2014-06-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11277899 |title=1080 battle gets political - National - NZ Herald News |publisher=Nzherald.co.nz |date= |accessdate=2014-06-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mills |first=Laura |url=http://www.greystar.co.nz/content/1080-political-party-proposed |title=1080 political party proposed &#124; Greymouth Star |publisher=Greystar.co.nz |date= |accessdate=2014-06-19}}</ref> The party's co-leaders are Bill Wallace and Mike Downard.<ref name="plist">{{cite web |url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PO1408/S00324/ban-1080-candidates-announced-for-2014-general-election.htm |title=Ban 1080 Candidates announced for 2014 General Election |publisher=Ban 1080 Party |date=2014-08-19 |accessdate=2014-08-19}}</ref>
The party's registration was cancelled on 28 February 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elections.org.nz/news-media/amendments-register-political-parties-28-february-2018 |title=Amendments to the Register of Political Parties - 28 February 2018 |publisher=Electoral Commission |date=28 February 2018 |accessdate=1 March 2018}}</ref>
== Policies == The Ban 1080 Party's stated policy is:
"to develop a pathway to a solution that includes the following elements: # To immediately stop the [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]]'s controlled aerial 1080 poison programme. # To develop a science-based, measurable programme that includes #* Species specific protection plans, #* Targeted pest control, using people not poison, #* Community conservation involvement. # To protect all waterways by ensuring no future aerial poison drops."<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ban1080.co.nz/party-policy/|title=Party Policy|last=|first=|date=|website=Ban 1080|publisher=|access-date=4 January 2017}}</ref> The party considers that the Department of Conservation "has an important task in working to protect and preserve our natural environment", but believes that aerial 1080 drops harm native species and are ineffective at controlling rat and stoat populations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ban1080.co.nz/|title=Aerial 1080 drops need to stop|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Ban 1080|access-date=4 January 2017}}</ref>
==History== ===2014 general election=== The Ban 1080 Party contested the [[New Zealand general election, 2014|2014 election]].<ref name="stuff1" /> The party applied for registration with the [[Electoral Commission (New Zealand)|Electoral Commission]] in mid-2014 and was approved on 8 August.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elections.org.nz/news-media/application-register-ban1080-party |title=Application to Register Ban1080 Party |publisher=New Zealand Electoral Commission |date=2014-07-08 |accessdate=2014-07-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elections.org.nz/news-media/registration-ban1080-and-logo |title=Registration of Ban1080 and Logo |publisher=New Zealand Electoral Commission |date=2014-08-08 |accessdate=2014-08-09}}</ref> On 19 August 2014, the party announced a party list of nine candidates, of which five were also electorate candidates.<ref name="plist" />
The party received 0.21% of the party vote, below the 5% threshold, and did not win any electorates, so did not win any seats in Parliament. Of the electoral candidates, the most successful was Pete Salter, who stood in [[West Coast-Tasman]]. He received 2,318 electoral votes, which was 6.5% of electoral votes cast and placed him fourth.
===2017 general election=== In the [[New Zealand general election, 2017|2017 election]] the Ban 1080 party nominated nine list candidates, including three electorate candidates. Pete Salter contested [[West Coast-Tasman]] again.<ref>http://www.elections.org.nz/events/2017-general-election/information-voters-who-when-and-where</ref> The Ban 1080 Party gained only 0.1% of the party vote (3,005) and failed to win any seats in the [[New Zealand House of Representatives]].<ref name="2017 general election results">{{cite web|title=2017 General Election - Official Result|url=http://www.electionresults.govt.nz/electionresults_2017/|publisher=[[Electoral Commission (New Zealand)|New Zealand Electoral Commission]]|accessdate=7 October 2017}}</ref>
