{{more footnotes|date=December 2010}} [[File:Image-Die Rampe Mahnmal Detail Kassel E R Nele.jpg|thumb|''Die Rampe'']] [[File:Windsbraut Dalbergplatz.jpg|thumb|''{{Interlanguage link multi|Windsbraut|de|3=Windsbraut (Skulptur}}'']]
'''E. R. Nele''' (born 15 March 1932) is a German sculptor famous for [[goldsmith]]ing and large scale metal sculptures.<ref>A concise history of modern sculpture. Sir Herbert Edward Read. Praeger, 1964. Page 235</ref>
Nele was born in [[Berlin]], the daughter of Marie-Louise (1908–1989) and [[Arnold Bode]] (1900–1977). She started her career in 1950 as a student of the [[Central School of Arts and Crafts]] in London. She participated in ''[[Documenta]] II'', organised by her father in 1959. She joined the [[Situationist International]], but was excluded in February 1962.
She learned to handle all sorts of metal and to weld steel for her artwork. After her return to Berlin she worked with the artist Hans Uhlmann during her time at the "Berliner Akademie" and later on at the "Studio Lacourière" in Paris. Since the late 1960s, Nele has lived and worked in [[Frankfurt]]. Since the early 1990s she has been teaching at the Universities of Frankfurt and Giessen.
Her best-known sculpture is named ''Die Rampe'', a [[Holocaust]] memorial dated from 1980.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hJpUAAAAMAAJ&q=Die+Rampe+sculpture&dq=Die+Rampe+sculpture&hl=en&ei=PeaGTPGOK4WglAeS_sGUDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3&ved=0CDsQ6AEwAg |title=Contemporary Artists: A-K |author=St. Sara Pendergast, Tom Pendergast|publisher= St. James Press |year= 2002}}</ref> Her latest metal sculpture at large scale is now located at the Dalbergplatz in Frankfurt-Höchst and named ''Windsbraut''.
E. R. Nele was awarded with the [[Goethe-Medaille für Kunst und Wissenschaft|Goetheplakette]] from the hands of the city's governing mayor [[Petra Roth]] on 12 September 2008 in the historic "Limpurgsaal". The Goetheplakette is awarded annually since 1947. Other awarded persons have been to date Horst-Eberhard Richter, Albert Speer, Thomas Bayrle and others.
